article.description: Lorenzen Wright scored 23 points, Brian Cardinal had 20 and the Memphis Grizzlies nearly blew a 13-point lead in the final 2:17 before beating the host Los Angeles Clippers 105-102 on Monday night for their fourth straight victory.
article.headline: Memphis nearly blows 13-point lead in final minutes
article.linkText: Grizzlies hold off Clippers for fourth win in row
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Injuries have crippled the Los Angeles Clippers' playoff hopes, while the Memphis Grizzlies are winning without three key players. Lorenzen Wright scored 23 points and Brian Cardinal had 20 for the Grizzlies, who nearly blew a 13-point lead in the final 2:17 before beating the Clippers 105-102 on Monday night for their fourth straight victory. "That's the way we've won the majority of our games this year," Shane Battier said. "It hasn't been pretty. It's been a rag-tag assortment of players at times, but we've found a way to win 34 games. A lot of guys have had to play because we've had so many injuries, so everyone feels they cam come in, step up and play at a high level." Memphis began a four-game trip without Pau Gasol, Bonzi Wells and Stromile Swift, but still managed to beat the Clippers on the road for the fourth straight time. Gasol, the team's leading scorer, missed his 17th game with an injured foot, Wells his second because of a herniated disc and Swift his sixth with a sprained left ankle. Battier, Cardinal and shooting guard Mike Miller have been pressed into starting roles, and all three excelled against the Clippers. Miller had 17 points and five assists, and Battier had 14 points. "They're one of the deepest teams in the league, and I think they're as well-poised to handle that as anybody," Clippers coach Mike Dunleavy said. "They have a lot of guys who play multiple positions, so they're more than two-deep at every position." Corey Maggette scored 37 points for the Clippers, and Bobby Simmons -- making a strong bid for the NBA's Most Improved Player award -- finished with 19 after making eight of his first 10 shots. Elton Brand had 17 points and six rebounds during a foul-plagued 32 minutes. The victory tied Memphis with Houston for sixth place in the Western Conference playoff race, 3½ games ahead of the Lakers and Denver. The Clippers' playoff chances have gone from promising to decent to unlikely over the past 4½ weeks, thanks to a 1-8 road trip that began with a 106-103 victory against the Grizzlies on Feb. 3 -- a game in which Memphis blew an 18-point lead. That was the last time the Clippers were at the .500 mark. They are 3-11 since. Trailing by 102-89 after Battier's short running jumper with 2:17 to play, the Clippers reeled off 11 straight points to close to 102-100 with 13.7 seconds left. Brand helped fuel the belated rally with six points. "They play well at home, so we knew they were capable of coming back. They did it before in Memphis," James Posey said. "They're a good team, despite their record." Posey gave Memphis some breathing room, converting his only two free throws of the game before Quinton Ross tipped in a long miss by Rick Brunson, making it a two-point game again with 7.9 seconds left. Maggette fouled Cardinal on the ensuing inbounds play following a timeout, and Cardinal made one of two from the line. That gave the Clippers a chance to force overtime with a 3-pointer, but Brunson's 3-point attempt bounded off the rim with 3 seconds left and Maggette was short on another 3 after getting the offensive rebound. "If we would have played the whole game the same way we played the last two minutes, we would have had a better chance of winning," said Chris Wilcox, who was the first player off the Clippers bench and picked up four fouls in his first 8 minutes on the court. The Grizzlies got a scare at the end in more ways than one. Posey accidentally elbowed Miller in the nose while trying to block Maggette's last-ditch shot, and Miller was down on the court for several anxious moments before he was led to the dressing room. He needed six stitches. The Clippers lost for the eighth time in nine meetings with Memphis. This result might have been different if not for the free-throw shooting of the usually reliable Maggette, who missed his first attempt on his last three trips to the line after making his first 10 in a row. The Grizzlies took a 78-71 lead into the fourth quarter, with all of their starters scoring in double figures by then. The Clippers committed eight turnovers in the third quarter -- as many as the Grizzlies made in the first three periods combined. "I could not count the mistakes we made that allowed them to get the lead they got," Dunleavy said. Maggette, held to 10 points in 39 minutes during Saturday's loss to Denver, scored 23 points in the first half against Memphis to help the Clippers take a 50-45 lead at intermission. Maggette and Simmons teamed up to score the Clippers' first 18 points, but they didn't take their first lead until a 3-pointer by rookie point guard Lionel Chalmers put them ahead 36-34 with 6:15 left in the second quarter.

Game notes
Memphis won the season series 3-1 after winning all four meetings in 2003-04. The Clippers are still the only team the Grizzlies have swept in a season series of more than two games. Memphis will attempt to complete a three-game sweep of Utah on Friday night. ... Thirteen of the Clippers' last 18 losses have been by margins of five points or fewer. They are 3-11 in games decided by three points or less. ... Memphis coach Mike Fratello is 24-4 against the Clippers, including 12-2 with Atlanta and 9-1 with Cleveland.
